text: Yep. So, okay, so it's sort of a complex system, but it's useful to just understand sort of the theory behind different stablecoin mechanisms. There's three, I would say, broad based categories of stablecoins. One is where there's collateral, but the collateral is not on the blockchain. So this is like USDC, this is tether. This is where the collateral is held by some central entity off the system. And then you can redeem the stablecoin that's on the blockchain for cash that's just in a bank account off the blockchain. So those systems are relatively simple conceptually. The problem is, of course, that there's a central entity that controls all that collateral. The second type is where the collateral is actually held on the blockchain. This is what the maker dao system does. Then there's kind of a third type that people generally refer to as seniorage or algorithmic stablecoins. And this is where the peg is backed up.
